article.description: Keith Langford and Wayne Simien were the latest Kansas players unaware of a rivalry with Kansas State.
article.headline: Jayhawks tally 24 assists, only seven turnovers
article.linkText: No problem: Kansas beats Kansas State again
article.story: MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) -- Aaron Miles could have done better in those times when nobody was guarding him and the clock was stopped. In traffic, though, he was near-perfect. Kansas' junior point guard matched a season high with 12 assists -- while committing only one turnover in 38 minutes -- in the 15th-ranked Jayhawks' 78-70 win over Kansas on Wednesday night. "I still need to hit my free throws better," said Miles, who was 6-for-11 from the line and finished with 13 points. Miles' teammates had few complaints, though. "He's been playing like that all year," said swingman Keith Langford, who led the Jayhawks with 19 points. "He's a pass-first point guard, and that's a dying breed." Wayne Simien added 16 points for Kansas (13-3, 5-0 Big 12), which withstood a second-half challenge for its 28th straight victory over the Wildcats and 21st in a row in Manhattan. Kansas State (9-7, 1-4) has not beaten the Jayhawks here since Jan. 29, 1983, and has never beaten them in Bramlage Coliseum, which opened in November 1988. The Wildcats last beat Kansas on Jan. 17, 1994, in Lawrence, where the Jayhawks won 73-67 earlier this month. Kansas State coach Jim Wooldridge bristled at talk of the streak. "I know everyone talks about the streak, but that is so out of the reality of what we're doing right now," said Wooldridge, who is in his fourth season. "We're just trying to get guys better right now. Even if that was Nebraska, we'd still feel like we were frustrated." Kansas State trailed by 21 points early in the second half but used a 10-0 run to cut the lead to nine with 8:15 left. Tim Ellis closed out the run with two quick baskets, including a tip-in that made it 64-55. But Kansas responded with a two free throws by Langford and a 3-pointer by J.R. Giddens for a 69-55 lead. "I just wish we'd had a little more time," Ellis said. "We needed that run a lot earlier." Jeremiah Massey's tip-in with 33.8 seconds left got Kansas State within 75-68, but by then it was too late. Kansas went 8-for-12 from the line in the final 2:27, with Miles going 6-for-10 over that span. Both teams missed plenty of chances to score on free throws. Kansas went 14-for-22 (64 percent), while the Wildcats were even worse at 12-for-21 (57 percent). "We tried to keep some life in us, and guy after guy goes to the line and misses free throws when we're in need of a basket," Wooldridge said. "When you get to the free throw line, you have to cash in." Massey led the Wildcats, who lost despite a 45-33 advantage on the boards, with 21 points and 12 rebounds. Jarrett Hart added 13 points, and Ellis finished with 11 points and 10 rebounds. Langford's 3-pointer gave Kansas a 30-17 lead with just under six minutes left in the first half. The Wildcats got back-to-back 3s from Massey and Hart to get within 30-23, but then went 1-for-5 from the free throw line in the final four minutes of the half. Miles hit a 3-pointer with three seconds left in the half for a 40-19 lead. Kansas had just one turnover in the first half, seven overall. A 13-3 run gave Kansas its biggest lead, 60-39, with just under 13 minutes left in the game. Freshman center David Padgett, who sat out Kansas' win in Lawrence with a stress fracture in his left foot, had eight points and four rebounds in 23 minutes for the Jayhawks on Wednesday.
